Introduction¶

Overview¶

Automatic speech recognition (ASR) modules have proved indispensability in any Natural Lanugage Processing solution. A deep learning powered automatic speech recognition system ,that accepts raw audio as an input and returns the predicted transcription of the spoken language, is designed in this project.

An bird's eye view on the pipeline used in this project is illustrated below followed by a general description about each part.

  • STEP 1: is a pre-processing step that converts raw audio to one of two feature representations that are commonly used for ASR.
  • STEP 2: is an acoustic model which accepts audio features as input and returns a probability distribution over all potential transcriptions.
  • STEP 3: takes the output from the acoustic model and returns a predicted transcription.

Data description¶

It is essential to begin by investigating the dataset that will be used to train and evaluate the pipeline. LibriSpeech is a large corpus of English-read speech, designed for training and evaluating models for ASR which contains 1000 hours of speech derived from audiobooks. However, a small portion of the data set is used to reduce the computation cost.

Any training example has the following attributes:

  • vis_text - transcribed text (label) for the training example.
  • vis_raw_audio - raw audio waveform for the training example.
  • vis_mfcc_feature - mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCCs) for the training example.
  • vis_spectrogram_feature - spectrogram for the training example.
  • vis_audio_path - the file path to the training example.

STEP 1: Acoustic Features for Speech Recognition¶

Two different pre-processing schemas is used to convert the raw audio to a feature representation that has historically proven successful for ASR models. Moreover, the acoustic model will accept this feature representation as an input. _Namely_, Spectograms and Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs) are used to map the input raw audio file into features ready to feed the deep learning models.

Spectrograms¶

The first option for an audio feature representation is the spectrogram. The code for calculating the spectrogram was borrowed from this repository.
The code returns the spectrogram as a 2D tensor, where the first (vertical) dimension indexes time, and the second (horizontal) dimension indexes frequency. To speed the convergence of the algorithm later, the spectrogram is normalized . Note that the mean value hovers around zero in the visualization below, and most entries in the tensor assume values close to zero.)

In [5]:
# plot normalized spectrogram
plot_spectrogram_feature(vis_spectrogram_feature)
# print shape of spectrogram
display(Markdown('**Shape of Spectrogram** : ' + str(vis_spectrogram_feature.shape)))

Shape of Spectrogram : (952, 161)

Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs)¶

The second option for an audio feature representation is MFCCs where python_speech_features is used for implementation. Just as with the spectrogram features, the MFCCs are normalized.

The main idea behind MFCC features is the same as spectrogram features: at each time window, the MFCC feature yields a feature vector that characterizes the sound within the window. Note that the MFCC feature is much lower-dimensional than the spectrogram feature, which could help an acoustic model to avoid overfitting to the training dataset.

STEP 2: Deep Neural Networks for Acoustic Modeling¶

In this section, various neural network architectures are used for acoustic modeling.

Having exprimented with relatively 4 simple models, some comparisons as well as insights are drawn before concluding with the final model that acheive the best performance.

Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)¶

The input data in speech recognition is a sequence of observations in the form of frame vectors from regular time intervals. The desired output is a series of symbols: phonemes, graphemes, or words. The basic problem is that the number of frames does not have a predictible correspondence to the number of the output symbols. For example, assume 20ms per frame, the following audio signals of the word "speech" spoken at two different speeds have about 300 frames in the first example and something like 850 frames in the second example, yet they should both be decoded as the six-letter word, "speech"

A Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) loss function can be calculated to train the network. When combined with the CTC decoding algorithm over the softmax output layer, the sequence-to-sequence transformation is achieved. The details of how this works are in the seminal paper on CTC by Alex Graves: Graves, Alex, et al. "Connectionist temporal classification: labelling unsegmented sequence data with recurrent neural networks." Proceedings of the 23rd international conference on Machine learning. ACM, 2006.

CTC Training¶

Graves derives an objective function to calculate the error between the labels expected and the softmax result. The function calculates all the possible paths and likelihoods for the softmax output layer and calculates the maximum log likelihood for the correct labeling. For example, a correct labeling of a "hello" utterance might have several valid paths with varying probabilities:

All models below are trained the acoustic model with the CTC loss criterion.

Model 0: RNN¶

Given their effectiveness in modeling sequential data, the first acoustic model used is an RNN. As shown in the figure below, the RNN takes the time sequence of audio features as an input.

At each time step, the speaker pronounces one of 28 possible characters, including each of the 26 letters in the English alphabet, along with a space character (" "), and an apostrophe (').

The output of the RNN at each time step is a vector of probabilities with 29 entries, where the $i$-th entry encodes the probability that the $i$-th character is spoken in the time sequence. (The extra 29th character is an empty "character" used to pad training examples within batches containing uneven lengths). The figure below shows an equivalent, rolled depiction of the RNN that shows the output layer in greater detail.

Model 4: Bidirectional RNN + TimeDistributed Dense¶

A single bidirectional RNN layer , before a (TimeDistributed) dense layer is experimented below. The added value of a bidirectional RNN is described well in this paper.

One shortcoming of conventional RNNs is that they are only able to make use of previous context. In speech recognition, where whole utterances are transcribed at once, there is no reason not to exploit future context as well. Bidirectional RNNs (BRNNs) do this by processing the data in both directions with two separate hidden layers which are then fed forwards to the same output layer.

Final Model: CNN + Deep Bidirectional RNN + TimeDistributed Dense¶

It is time to draft the final architecture by merely combining the explored layers above into a deeper architecture.

Architecture Description¶

Based on the results so far, the final model is built upon models above and included the ideas that showed the potential. More spesifically, this model uses Convolutational Neural Network (CNN) to extract spatial patterns from the audio features before feeding it to a deep bidirectional Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) to learn the temporal patterns from both directions. In addition, this final model employs early stopping mechanism as well regularized RNN layers to reduce overfitting.

In other words, the model combines models 3,4 and 5 analyzed above due to their promising results.

Model Evaluation and Comparisons¶

To evaluate the performance of the drafted deep learning models, the training and validation loss are plotted for each model.

Learning curves¶

In [1]:
from glob import glob
import numpy as np
import _pickle as pickle
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
sns.set_style(style='white')

# obtain the paths for the saved model history
all_pickles = sorted(glob("results/*.pickle"))
# extract the name of each model
model_names = [item[8:-7] for item in all_pickles]
# extract the loss history for each model
valid_loss = [pickle.load( open( i, "rb" ) )['val_loss'] for i in all_pickles]
train_loss = [pickle.load( open( i, "rb" ) )['loss'] for i in all_pickles]
# save the number of epochs used to train each model
num_epochs = [len(valid_loss[i]) for i in range(len(valid_loss))]

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,5))

# plot the training loss vs. epoch for each model
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(121)
for i in range(len(all_pickles)):
    ax1.plot(np.linspace(1, num_epochs[i], num_epochs[i]), 
            train_loss[i], label=model_names[i])
# clean up the plot
ax1.legend()  
ax1.set_xlim([1, max(num_epochs)])
ax1.grid()
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Training Loss')

# plot the validation loss vs. epoch for each model
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(122)
for i in range(len(all_pickles)):
    ax2.plot(np.linspace(1, num_epochs[i], num_epochs[i]), 
            valid_loss[i], label=model_names[i])
# clean up the plot
ax2.legend()  
ax2.set_xlim([1, max(num_epochs)])
ax2.grid()
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Validation Loss')
plt.show()

Observations¶

  • All models exhibit acceptable learning curves except ,unsurprisngly, for the very simple model which saturates at very high loss values for both training and validation curves.
  • All other models have comparable values for training and validation at each epoch which reveals that the model is really learning and no overfitting occurs.
  • The deep RNN model, surprsingly, did not manage to learn the complexity of the data so well and stopped training by EarlyStopping mechanism which watches if the validation error doesn't improve over pre-specified epochs window.
  • Feature extraction using CNN proved superior performance over all other networks that consiste of RNN only including the deep RNN model. This suggests using CNN layers to improve the model in the final run to get more enhanced performance.

STEP 3: Obtain Predictions¶

The final step is to decode the predictions of the acoustic model.

In [20]:
import numpy as np
from data_generator import AudioGenerator
from keras import backend as K
from utils import int_sequence_to_text
from IPython.display import Audio

def get_predictions(index, partition, input_to_softmax, model_path):
    """ Print a model's decoded predictions
    Params:
        index (int): The example you would like to visualize
        partition (str): One of 'train' or 'validation'
        input_to_softmax (Model): The acoustic model
        model_path (str): Path to saved acoustic model's weights
    """
    # load the train and test data
    data_gen = AudioGenerator()
    data_gen.load_train_data()
    data_gen.load_validation_data()
    
    # obtain the true transcription and the audio features 
    if partition == 'validation':
        transcr = data_gen.valid_texts[index]
        audio_path = data_gen.valid_audio_paths[index]
        data_point = data_gen.normalize(data_gen.featurize(audio_path))
    elif partition == 'train':
        transcr = data_gen.train_texts[index]
        audio_path = data_gen.train_audio_paths[index]
        data_point = data_gen.normalize(data_gen.featurize(audio_path))
    else:
        raise Exception('Invalid partition!  Must be "train" or "validation"')
        
    # obtain and decode the acoustic model's predictions
    input_to_softmax.load_weights(model_path)
    prediction = input_to_softmax.predict(np.expand_dims(data_point, axis=0))
    output_length = [input_to_softmax.output_length(data_point.shape[0])] 
    pred_ints = (K.eval(K.ctc_decode(
                prediction, output_length)[0][0])+1).flatten().tolist()
    
    # play the audio file, and display the true and predicted transcriptions
    print('-'*80)
    Audio(audio_path)
    print('True transcription:\n' + '\n' + transcr)
    print('-'*80)
    print('Predicted transcription:\n' + '\n' + ''.join(int_sequence_to_text(pred_ints)))
    print('-'*80)

Conclusions and Future Work¶

Limitations and Conclusions¶

  • The end model reveals superior performance over all previous models which indicates moving in the right direction toward more robust models.
  • The loss value still quite large indicating the complexity of the problem. However, networks with convolutional neural networks showed potential for extracting relevent patterns from audio features that help the acoustic model produce more advanced transcriptions.
  • The training data is truncated to be able to produce meaningful results in this project. However, adding more data could introduce more advanced transcriptions.
  • The models so far were not experimented with test (unseen) data which is expected to perform similar or even worst.
  • Including of bidirectional RNN showed slight improvment over similar unidirectional RNN structure. Nevertheless, more deep RNN does not seem to be helpful in learning process.
  • Adding dropout regularization as well as early stopping mechanism helped reduce overfitting significantly while training the final model.
  • The state-of-the-art models take 3-6 weeks of training on a single GPU which is out of scope for this educational project.

Future Work¶

  • Adding language model to the decoder which is the defacto standard way to improve the results nowadays.
  • Expriement with deep learning algorithms that accepts raw audio input directly (i.e., without feature extraction step)
  • ُExperiment the models using LSTM instead of GRU.
  • Add dilated convolutions and max pooling layer to the convoluation network that works on feature extraction.
  • Feed all models with MFCC features instead of Spectograms to reduce overfitting.
